<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="65" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,398,888]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,329,514,540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species looks somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[826,994,514,539]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Pyroderces" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sarcogypsa">
<emphasis box="[826,994,514,539]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">P. sarcogypsa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated from it by the forewing ochreous yellow mottled silvery white lines (
<figureCitation box="[811,880,553,579]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1885,1909]" captionTargetBox="[256,1325,744,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[226,1360,731,1885]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pyroderces argyrogrammos (Zeller). a, adult; b, male genitalia (gen. slide No. ZZW 07158); c, female genitalia (gen. slide No. ZZW 07309)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/190978/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
Fig. 
<number box="[868,880,553,579]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
a); in male genitalia, the valvae lack the basal lobes, and the manica is narrowed distally, with a truncate apex (
<figureCitation box="[903,970,592,618]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1885,1909]" captionTargetBox="[256,1325,744,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[226,1360,731,1885]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pyroderces argyrogrammos (Zeller). a, adult; b, male genitalia (gen. slide No. ZZW 07158); c, female genitalia (gen. slide No. ZZW 07309)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/190978/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
Fig. 
<number box="[958,970,592,618]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
b); in female genitalia, the signa consist of a pair of sclerotized carinae of irregular shape (
<figureCitation box="[745,813,630,656]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1885,1909]" captionTargetBox="[256,1325,744,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[226,1360,731,1885]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pyroderces argyrogrammos (Zeller). a, adult; b, male genitalia (gen. slide No. ZZW 07158); c, female genitalia (gen. slide No. ZZW 07309)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/190978/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
Fig. 
<number box="[801,813,630,656]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
c). In 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" box="[886,1179,630,656]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Pyroderces" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sarcogypsa">
<emphasis box="[886,1049,631,656]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">P. sarcogypsa</emphasis>
(Meyrick)
</taxonomicName>
, the male valvae bear setose basal lobes and the female signa consist of paired rows of densely compact spines of similar shape and size.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
